narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: I'd recommend it if a student enjoyed buildings and philosophical mindsets. Those who think quantitatively though, may find themselves unsure of how to pull magical orations out of no where about parts of a building normal people overlook (ie placement of nails, angles of archways, shapes of windows, and all of their meanings).
I would definitely commend this because it was a really fun class. I really enjoyed the learning, discussions and drawing assignments. You also get an intimate setting.

This class was a great way to see a new side of both architecture and utopia. The class was balanced between the two, and had traditional reading aspects as well as creative projects that were fun to do. I would absolutely recommend this class to anyone who is looking to explore architecture (since it is one of the very first opportunities to take a class in the department). I'd also recommend it to anyone else because it is an interesting exploration of things that are usually taught in different contexts.
I would definitely recommend this course. It's a great introduction to certain ideas and concepts in architecture, and the seminar structure of the class was a really great experience.
The workload is very light and if you have a small class, discussions can be very fun. You don't learn much though, and I felt like I came out of the class having gained very little.
